    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-07-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-07-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="170"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d170">
                <head>170. Letter From Secretary of Defense <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1" type="from"
                        >McNamara</persName> to Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_RD3"
                        type="to">Rusk</persName>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d170fn0">Source: Department of State, <gloss
                            target="#t_SS1">S/S</gloss>-<gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files:
                        Lot 72 <gloss target="#t_D1">D</gloss> 316, <gloss target="#t_NSAM1"
                            >NSAM</gloss> No. 242. Confidential. A copy was sent to <persName
                            corresp="#p_BMG2">McGeorge Bundy</persName>. The source text is Tab A to
                        an undated memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_JUA1">U. Alexis
                            Johnson</persName> to Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD3"
                            >Rusk</persName>. As summarized in Johnson’s memorandum, <persName
                            corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>’s letter was an outgrowth of
                        correspondence on military sales between <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1"
                            >McNamara</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_BDE1">Bell</persName>.
                            <persName corresp="#p_BDE1">Bell</persName>’s June 24 letter to
                            <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>’s June 28 reply, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>’s June 27 memorandum to <persName
                            corresp="#p_BWP1">William Bundy</persName> are Tab C. Tab D is printed
                        as <ref target="#d171">Document 171</ref>. <persName corresp="#p_JUA1">U.
                            Alexis Johnson</persName> transmitted his memorandum to <persName
                            corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName> (with all its tabs) under cover of an
                        undated memorandum to <persName corresp="#p_BDE1">Bell</persName> asking for
                        his concurrence.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-07-09">July 9, 1963</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Dean</hi>: The following statements by the President
                    were issued as a part of National Security Action Memorandum No. 242, dated 9
                    May 1963: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>"It is essential that we make every effort to prosecute the program of
                            selling U.S. equipment to allies.”</p>
                        <p>"Not only will this decrease the net outflow of gold from this country,
                            but it also ties in our military aid to foreign policy.”</p>
                        <p>"Will you please assure that those concerned are properly informed,
                            including appropriate Members of Congress, those concerned in other
                            departments of government, as well as those in the Department of
                                Defense.”<note n="1" xml:id="d170fn1">The full text of <gloss
                                    target="#t_NSAM1">NSAM</gloss> No. 242 is Tab B to Johnson’s
                                undated memorandum to Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD3"
                                    >Rusk</persName>. The President issued <gloss target="#t_NSAM1"
                                    >NSAM</gloss> No. 242 following receipt of a May 7 memorandum
                                from <persName corresp="#p_NPH1">Nitze</persName>, which offered
                                reasons for the Australian Government’s purchase of French Mirage
                                airplanes. A copy of <persName corresp="#p_NPH1">Nitze</persName>’s
                                memorandum is in the Washington National Records Center, <gloss
                                    target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 286, <gloss target="#t_AID1"
                                    >AID</gloss> Administrator Files: <gloss target="#t_FRC1"
                                    >FRC</gloss> 67 <gloss target="#t_A1">A</gloss> 1530, Military
                                Assistance, <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> 1964.</note>
                        </p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>I have directed all appropriate elements of the Department of Defense to
                    aggressively pursue the prosecution of such a program.</p>
                <p>In keeping with the President’s expressed desire, I suggest that you advise
                    appropriate personnel in your Department of the policy contained in the above
                    quoted remarks. I further suggest that you enjoin those concerned to keep this
                    policy clearly in mind as we seek solutions to the many difficult problems
                    involved in prosecuting such a program.</p>
                <p>Sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Bob</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
